\title{ An overview of the functions in this package }

\description{
The vegsoup package provides classes and methods to manipulate vegetation (community composition) data. It can be viewed as a data base system. Vegetation data consists of at least of two related tables -- a species matrix and a table of measurements taken at a site (sampling unit or \enc{relev√©e}{relevee}). If taxonomic identity, or traits of species is a concern an additional table has to be tightly linked to the species matrix. Moreover, if spatial representation (e.g. plot coordinates and/or polygons) needs to be addressed another data layer has to be included. In the most complete case we end up with up to five independent R objects. Indexing and manipulation easily get cumbersome in this situation and the general workflow is hindered by a serious amount of code that ensures linking of objects.

The package should be particularly useful when \dots.

Below is a list of functions grouped by theme.
}

\details{

The package implements classes for vegetation data (see \link{Vegsoup-class}) and supports
  \itemize{
    \item data to be structured in layers/strata.
    \item several cover scales and conversions thereof.
    \item taxonomic treatment including species traits.
    \item standardizations and dissimilarity measures of the species data.
    \item creation of species and dissimilarity/distance matrices.
    \item indexing, extract, replace and sample operations.
    \item row and column aggregation
    \item merging of objects
    \item coerce methods
    \item output methods (Latex and plain text files)
    \item spatial methods
    \item plotting methods
  }

